## Plan Summary

**Only one file needs to change: `src/routes.ts`**

Here's what I found and what the plan does:

### Codebase Overview
- **15 in-memory users** in `src/data.ts`
- `GET /users` currently returns `res.json(users)` — a flat array, no pagination
- **Tests already exist** in `tests/routes.test.ts` expecting the paginated shape — they're currently failing

### The Change (single handler update)

```typescript
// BEFORE
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  res.json(users);
});

// AFTER
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  const page  = parseInt(req.query.page  as string, 10) || 1;
  const limit = parseInt(req.query.limit as string, 10) || 10;

  const total      = users.length;
  const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);
  const start      = (page - 1) * limit;
  const data       = users.slice(start, start + limit); // naturally [] when out of range

  res.json({ data, pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages } });
});
```

### Why this works for every test case
| Test | Params | Expected | Result |
|------|--------|----------|--------|
| Default | none | 10 items, page 1, total 15, totalPages 2 | ✅ `slice(0,10)` |
| Page 2 | `?page=2&limit=10` | 5 items | ✅ `slice(10,20)` → 5 items |
| Custom limit | `?limit=5` | 5 items, totalPages 3 | ✅ `slice(0,5)` |
| Out of range | `?page=100` | empty data, no error | ✅ `slice(990,1000)` → `[]` |
| Existing tests | `/users/1`, `/users/999` | unchanged | ✅ not touched |
